    "description": "This blog provides a guide to the study of Secretarial Audit, the planning and performing of an audit, the stages of an audit, the ICSI auditing standards, the matters relating to professional misconduct while obtaining professional work and the acceptance of a secretarial audit. ",
    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Which companies are required to conduct a secretarial audit?",
        "answer": "Under the Companies Act, 2013, every listed company and certain classes of public companies meeting specific thresholds must conduct a secretarial audit annually.  Additionally, companies that have issued certain types of securities or have specific structures might also require it. It is becoming increasingly common for private companies to voluntarily conduct secretarial audits for better governance even when not legally mandated. The main point to be kept in mind is that paid-up share capital of ₹50 crore or more, or turnover of ₹250 crore or more are those specific type of companies."
      },
      {
        "question": "Who can conduct a secretarial audit?",
        "answer": "Only a practicing company secretary (PCS) who is a member of the Institute of Company Secretaries of India (ICSI) can conduct a secretarial audit. They must have a valid certificate of practice and should not have any disqualifications. The company secretary who is in whole-time employment of the company cannot conduct their own company's secretarial audit, independence is crucial."
      },
      {
        "question": " How is a secretarial audit different from a financial audit?",
        "answer": "A financial audit examines your company's financial statements, the numbers, accounting policies, revenue recognition, and so on. It's conducted by a chartered accountant. A secretarial audit, on the other hand, looks at legal and regulatory compliances, board procedures, statutory filings, adherence to corporate laws, maintenance of registers and records. Both are essential, but they examine completely different aspects of your company."
      },
      {
        "question": "How long does a secretarial audit typically take?",
        "answer": "The duration varies widely based on the company's size, complexity, and compliance status. For a small, well-organized company with straightforward operations, it might take a week or two. For a large, listed company with multiple subsidiaries and complex transactions, it could take several weeks to a couple of months. The key is ensuring the auditor has sufficient time to do thorough work, rushing an audit defeats its entire purpose."
      },
      {
        "question": "What happens if the secretarial audit uncovers non-compliances?",
        "answer": "The auditor is required to report all material non-compliances in their audit report. This report goes to the board of directors and is attached to the board's report submitted to shareholders. The company then needs to take corrective action. Depending on the nature and severity of non-compliance, there might be penalties from regulators. However, discovering issues through your own audit is far better than having regulators discover them during inspections, it demonstrates good faith and allows for proactive remediation."
      },
      {
        "question": "Can a secretarial auditor provide advisory services to the same company?",
        "answer": "This is a nuanced area. While there's no blanket prohibition, the auditor must maintain independence and objectivity. If advisory services could compromise this independence or create a situation where the auditor is essentially auditing their own advice, that's problematic. Many professionals and companies prefer to keep audit and advisory services separate to avoid even the appearance of conflict. When advisory is provided, it should be clearly documented, and safeguards should be in place to maintain audit integrity."
      },
      {
        "question": "What are the consequences for auditors who don't follow professional standards?",
        "answer": "Professional misconduct can lead to serious consequences. The ICSI has a disciplinary mechanism that can investigate complaints against company secretaries. Penalties range from warnings and fines to suspension or cancellation of the certificate of practice. In severe cases, the member can even be removed from ICSI membership. Beyond professional penalties, there could be reputational damage and, in cases involving fraud or serious negligence, even legal action"
      },
      {
        "question": "Can a company change its secretarial auditor mid-term?",
        "answer": "While possible, it's generally not advisable unless there are compelling reasons like misconduct, fundamental disagreements on significant matters, or the auditor's inability to complete the work. Changing auditors frequently can raise red flags with stakeholders and regulators. If a change is necessary, proper professional courtesy protocols must be followed, including communication between the incoming and outgoing auditors. The reasons for change might need to be disclosed in regulatory filings."
      },
      {
        "question": "What should a company do to prepare for a secretarial audit?",
        "answer": "Preparation makes the audit smoother and more efficient. First, ensure all statutory registers are updated and maintained properly. Organize minutes of all board and committee meetings, general meetings, and related documentation. Compile all filings made with regulators during the year. Have a list of all applicable laws and compliance requirements ready. Designate a point person who can coordinate with the auditor and arrange access to documents and personnel. Finally, be transparent, hiding issues only makes things worse. The audit is meant to help you improve, not punish you."
      },
      {
        "question": "How much does a secretarial audit cost?",
        "answer": "This varies tremendously based on company size, complexity, geographical location, and the professional's experience. A small company might pay anywhere from ₹25,000 to ₹1,00,000, while large, complex organizations could pay several lakhs. Remember, the lowest fee isn't always the best choice, adequate remuneration is necessary for thorough work. The engagement letter should clearly specify fees, so there are no surprises later."
      }
    ],
