    "author": "Swarnav Biswas",
    "category": "GetLawyer",
    "description": "The Real Estate (Regulation and Development) Act, 2016 (RERA) has fundamentally transformed the Indian property market by acting as a robust protective shield for homebuyers against unethical practices like delayed possession, deceptive advertising, and substandard construction. Acting as a specialized regulatory body, RERA empowers aggrieved buyers to seek effective legal remedies through a streamlined, state-specific online complaint process. This systematic framework not only ensures developer accountability but also provides a transparent and accessible pathway for dispute resolution, allowing homeowners to secure their rights and investments without the complexities of traditional litigation.",
    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Who is eligible to file a RERA complaint?",
        "answer": " Any individual who feels aggrieved may submit a complaint. This encompasses a homebuyer (allottee) acting independently or a collective of homebuyers. Additionally, an association representing allottees is permitted to file a complaint."
      },
      {
        "question": "Who can I file a complaint against? ",
        "answer": "You are entitled to file a complaint against any promoter (builder/developer), real estate agent, or even another allottee for any breach or violation of the provisions outlined in the RERA Act or the associated rules and regulations."
      },
      {
        "question": "Is it necessary for a project to be RERA registered in order to file a complaint?",
        "answer": "\n Although RERA regulations primarily pertain to registered projects, you may still file a complaint against a builder of an unregistered project if it fulfills the registration criteria (land area exceeding 500 sq. meters or more than 8 apartments) and should have been registered. The authority is empowered to take action against the builder for failing to register."
      },
      {
        "question": "What are typical grounds for filing a RERA complaint?",
        "answer": "The most prevalent reasons include:\n\nDelays in property possession.\nStructural flaws or substandard construction quality within 5 years of possession.\nRequests for advance payments surpassing 10% of the property cost prior to the signing of the agreement.\nInconsistencies in the carpet area.\nDeceptive advertisements or false assurances regarding amenities."
      },
      {
        "question": "5. What is the timeframe for resolving a complaint?",
        "answer": " The RERA Act stipulates that the regulatory authority should strive to resolve complaints within 60 days from the date of submission. However, this period may be extended if there are justifiable reasons, which must be documented in writing."
      },
      {
        "question": "6. Am I allowed to withdraw my complaint after it has been filed?",
        "answer": " Yes, you have the option to withdraw your complaint at any point before the RERA authority issues a final order. You will need to submit a withdrawal application, and the authority may grant it, occasionally with specific conditions."
      }
    ],
    "content": "<!--StartFragment--><p>The Real Estate (Regulation and Development) Act, 2016 (RERA) has significantly transformed the landscape for homebuyers in India, offering essential protection against unethical practices within the real estate industry. Should you encounter challenges such as delayed possession, deceptive advertisements, or substandard construction quality, submitting a complaint to your state's RERA authority serves as a systematic and effective remedy.</p>\n<p>This blog aims to provide a comprehensive guide on the procedure for filing a RERA complaint, illustrated with a straightforward infographic, and will address the most commonly asked questions.</p>\n<h3><strong>The 6-Step RERA Complaint Filing Journey</strong></h3>\n<p>Below is a visual depiction of the typical process for submitting a complaint online via your state's RERA portal.</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th><strong>Step</strong></th>\n<th><strong>Action</strong></th>\n<th><strong>Description</strong></th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>1</strong></td>\n<td>📁 <strong>Gather Documents</strong></td>\n<td>Collect all relevant papers: Agreement for Sale, payment receipts, booking form, correspondence with the builder, etc.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>2</strong></td>\n<td>💻 <strong>Visit State Portal</strong></td>\n<td>Identify and visit the official RERA website of the state where your property is located (e.g., MahaRERA, UP RERA).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>3</strong></td>\n<td>👤 <strong>Register / Login</strong></td>\n<td>Create a user account on the portal using your email and mobile number. Log in if you already have an account.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>4</strong></td>\n<td>📝 <strong>Fill Complaint Form</strong></td>\n<td>Navigate to the \"Complaint Registration\" section. Enter details of the complainant, respondent (builder), project, and the nature of your grievance.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>5</strong></td>\n<td>💳 <strong>Pay the Fee</strong></td>\n<td>Pay the prescribed complaint fee online. This amount varies from state to state (typically between ₹1,000 to ₹5,000).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>6</strong></td>\n<td>📤 <strong>Submit &amp; Track</strong></td>\n<td>Upload supporting documents, submit the form, and note down the complaint reference number for future tracking.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3><strong>Comprehensive Step-by-Step Manual</strong></h3>\n<p>While the infographic provides a brief overview, let us explore the specifics of each step in detail.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 1: Collect Your Documents</strong>\nPrior to commencing, it is essential to be organized. Ensure that you have scanned copies of all required documents. This generally includes your Sale Agreement, evidence of payments made to the builder, a brochure or advertisement copy, and any email or letter correspondence that substantiates your claim.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2: Locate Your State's RERA Website</strong>\nRERA operates at the state level. You cannot submit a complaint on a national website. It is necessary to find the official website of the Real Estate Regulatory Authority for the particular state where your project is located. A straightforward web search such as \"RERA [State Name] official website\" will lead you there.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 3: Register an Account</strong>\nOn the state portal, you will need to register as a complainant. This typically requires you to provide basic personal information such as your name, contact number, and email address to create a login ID and password.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 4: Complete the Complaint Form</strong>\nOnce you are logged in, search for a link that states \"File a Complaint,\" \"Complaint Registration,\" or something similar. You will be asked to provide detailed information:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Complainant Information:</strong> Your name, address, and contact details.</li>\n<li><strong>Respondent Information:</strong> Name, address, and RERA registration number of the builder/developer/agent.</li>\n<li><strong>Project Information:</strong> Name and location of the project.</li>\n<li><strong>Complaint Information:</strong> A clear and concise account of the facts regarding your grievance, the relief you are seeking, and any interim reliefs, if applicable.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Step 5: Remit the Filing Fee</strong>\nAfter entering the details and uploading documents, you will be directed to a payment gateway. The fee for filing a complaint varies across India and is determined by the specific RERA regulations of each state. Payment is typically accepted through net banking, credit/debit cards, or UPI.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 6: Submit and Monitor</strong>\nUpon successful payment and submission, the system will generate a unique complaint reference number.</p>\n<!-- notionvc: 422bc45c-8671-48be-87da-40e4bd79a049 --><!--EndFragment-->"
